messages.content:
Here's a simple HTML5 web app that crops a 100x100 pixel section from the provided image, tiles it as the background, and includes all CSS and JavaScript in a single code block. Given that I cannot fetch external images, please make sure to download the image and host it properly or modify the `url` to point to the image.

Here is the code you can use:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Tiled Background Example</title>
    <style>
        body, html {
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            height: 100%;
            display: flex;
            justify-content: center;
            align-items: center;
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }
        .background {
            background-image: url('https://s.h4ks.com/5851d133/file_457.jpg');
            background-size: 100px 100px; /* Set to the size of the cropped area */
            background-repeat: repeat; /* Tile the image */
            width: 100%; 
            height: 100%;
            position: absolute; /* Cover entire page */
            z-index: -1; /* Send background behind other content */
        }
        .content {
            position: relative; /* To allow z-index to work */
            padding: 20px;
            background-color: rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.8); /* Background to make text readable */
            border-radius: 10px;
            box-shadow: 0px 0px 10px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <div class="background"></div>
    <div class="content">
        <h1>Welcome to my Web App</h1>
        <p>This is an example of a tiled background using a cropped section of an image.</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
```

### Notes:
1. **Image URL**: Ensure that the image URL points directly to the image you want to use, or replace it with a valid path to a local image if you're running this file offline.
2. **Cropped Image**: The code uses `background-size: 100px 100px;` to assume that the desired 100x100 area is cropped from the image and tiled. Adjust the sizing in the CSS if you want different behavior.
3. **Content and Style**: The app has a semi-transparent white box to improve text readability against the tiled background.
4. **Testing**: Open the code in a web browser to see the result.
